	(2034,1,'2016-01-12 11:39:20','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<h2>Why We Should All Use Technology to Choose Our Careers</h2>\r\nOne of the most difficult decisions that you have to make in life is which career you are going to aim for. Whether you make this decision in high school / university or after being in the workforce, it can affect the direction you take for the rest of your life. The wrong choice can result in years of wasted time and money studying for a career you won\'t enjoy. For too long this huge decision has pretty much been based on flicking through a careers guide and gut instinct. however psychometric career testing technology can now provide an accurate and valuable tool to assist your decision making process and present suitable career options that you may not have previously considered.\r\n\r\nWhen you consider that enjoying the main tasks of your career is one of the dominant predictors of success (and happiness) and that this technology helps you identify careers that you will enjoy, it seems like a no-brainer that we should all be taking advantage psychometric testing to help us make better decisions. Let\'s learn more about psychometric testing and how to take advantage of this new technology.\r\n<h3>What are Psychometric Tests?</h3>\r\nThe first rudimentary forms of psychometric tests were originally invented by the Chinese around 2200BC for the purpose of evaluating members of their civil service\'s suitability for job roles. Similar processes have also been documented in Ancient Egypt. However psychometric testing really took off in the early twentieth century when they were widely used by the British and American armies to classify new recruits and to find job placements for men leaving the service. Following this they gained acceptance and widespread use in large corporations. Ongoing research and development has lead to significant improvements in accuracy and validity that have seen various versions found across the world and taken by a wide range of people. They are now virtually impossible to cheat on and truly depict a very accurate psychological profile of the individual. For this reason, many employers use these tests for placing the best candidates. Increasing education providers are using psychometrics to help match students with suitable careers.\r\n\r\nWhen it comes to assessing which career, or job, is best for a person, there are basically two different areas of psychometric tests:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><u>Personality</u> - tests personality traits and behavioural patterns to assess Suitability for a career path (would you enjoy it) through , such as whether they are selfish or empathetic, introverted or outgoing, and so on. There are no right or wrong answers to your unique personality.</li>\r\n	<li><u>Aptitude</u> - assesses skills and performance, such as Numerical Reasoning, Verbal Reasoning, Critical Thinking and Situational Judgement</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nPersonality testing is important in gaining understanding of how you think and react to situations while Aptitude testing can demonstrate that cognitive abilities are sufficient to perform in the job. Both are valuable tools for working out your suitability for a career and are highly recommended before making a one of the biggest decisions of your life.\r\n<h3>How They Help Us Choose Our Careers</h3>\r\nThe purpose of psychometric testing is to dig deep down into what people really mean. For example, everyone will say that they want to work with people, but working with people comes in many different forms. It could mean they want to help others. Or it could mean they would be a good leader among people. A psychometric test will find out exactly which direction is most suitable, therefore tailoring job suggestions more accurately. It can assess the career options that have the most common tasks that you will enjoy.\r\n\r\nPerhaps the main thing to remember about psychometric tests is this though: most people, no matter how young or old, dont truly understand their own personality and therefore dont know how they will react to different careers. The best psychometric testing can provide a scientific, yet unbiased look into your future career path while providing insights into Emotional Intelligence (EI) by allowing you to view and reflect on your unique personality traits and behaviours. This technology allows people to make informed decisions on their careers without solely relying on traditional gut instinct. Even if you have a set and clear goal in life, you should take one, as they could challenge your perceptions of what a good career might be and save you a lot of hassle in the future.\r\n\r\nForsee\'s Career Navigator is the most advanced career matching tool on the market. It only takes 20 minutes to complete and provides a range of suitable careers that you can shortlist and drill down further into what exactly you will and will not enjoy about a particular career path. With cutting edge technology to help us make our decision, shouldn\'t everyone be in a job they love?\r\n\r\nCareer Navigator is currently available for a free trial here.','Why we should all use Psychometric Testing to choose our careers','','draft','open','open','','','','','2016-01-12 11:39:20','2016-01-12 00:39:20','',0,'http://forsee.192.168.1.200.xip.io:8888/?p=2034',5,'post','',0),
