	(2042,1,'2016-01-12 11:41:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','If you ever want to float a question in the interest of energizing a floundering barbecue, dinner party or social hour, try this one: How many times does the average person change careers in a lifetime?\r\n\r\n<em>Well, define your terms, </em>people might say  and rightly so. Not every job is a career because everyone defines the terms differently. (See? People around you have perked up already.)\r\n\r\nThen drill down to the matter of age. Although you might assume Baby Boomers have more staying power than millennials  or those born between 1977 and 1997  Boomers held, on average, <a href=\"http://www.bls.gov/nls/nlsfaqs.htm#anch41\" target=\"_blank\">11.7 jobs between the ages of 18 and 48,</a> according to the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics.\r\n\r\nStill, at least one significant study  Multiple Generations @ Work  revealed that 91 percent of millennials plan to <a href=\"http://futureworkplace.com/wp-content/uploads/MultipleGenAtWork_infographic.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">stay in a job for less than three years,</a> which means they will hold between 15 and 20 positions during their work lives.\r\n\r\n<strong>This career navigator leads the way</strong>\r\n\r\nFor the sake of neutralizing semantics, let\'s call it a \"career\" rather than a \"job.\" And as anyone who is trying to navigate the process of settling on a career surely knows, the process can be fraught with stress, fear and indecision.\r\n\r\nFortunately, for people of any age, there is Forsee\'s Career Navigator System  a cutting-edge and highly accurate psychometric testing tool that assesses personality traits and interests and then suggests suitable career options based on those insights.\r\n\r\nSo fittingly named, this new technology takes only 20 minutes to complete. It reduces the stress of choosing a career. It mitigates the fear. And breeds confidence inn your decisions. Following your completion of the online questionnaire the system provides you a list of ranked list of suitable careers. From here you can shortlist your favourites and dig deeper into exactly what you are likely to enjoy and dislike about individual careers.\r\n\r\nWith your shortlist of careers displayed right before your eyes, you need to consider these four questions.\r\n\r\n<strong>Final questions to consider</strong>\r\n\r\nThe four questions on our checklist are:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Does this career sound interesting?</strong> Not everyone is hard-wired to jump and down, heart pumping, over a career in order to thrive in it. But on some gut level, the career should appeal to you and trigger a desire to learn more about it.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Does this career involve tasks that you could see yourself doing, enjoying and fulfilling with success? </strong>Now here\'s a question worthy of serious thought  and perhaps future exploration with a someone who belongs to that career group. Every job  and career  involves tasks that are mundane or underwhelming. But overall, you should be able to picture yourself in the career  and the picture should be positive.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Will this career fulfill your essential needs? </strong>Only you know your true priorities, be they the promise of challenge, opportunity or advancement, work-life balance or salary. (Your answer might be all of the above.) Now is the time to invoke another semantical difference: what you want in a career and what you need from it.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Is this career choice in demand in the marketplace?</strong> Up to this point, you might think that choosing a career is purely an emotional decision. But it pays to be practical, at least if you wish to remain gainfully employed and earning an income. Here again, reputable working professionals can give you the lowdown, as can trade groups and associations. When it comes to career forecasts, the bureau of labor statistics also is known for being spot-on.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nResearch shows: the single biggest driver of career success is whether a career is a good match for your distinctive combination of personality traits and interests. You can successfully navigate this unknown by using data driven research derived from the people who have gone before you. Forsee\'s Career Navigator is currently available for a free trial here. Give yourself the best chance of making a great career choice!','Don\'t be afraid of career change by answering these four questions','','draft','open','open','','','','','2016-01-12 11:41:01','2016-01-12 00:41:01','',0,'http://forsee.192.168.1.200.xip.io:8888/?p=2042',1,'post','',0),
